paragraphs.title: Introduction
paragraphs.text:
%md

This notebook provides an illustrative workflow that follows the [Kounkel and Covey (2019)](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2019AJ....158..122K/abstract) kinematic analysis of Gaia DR2 which used unsupervised ML techniques to identify kinematic structures in five-dimensional parameter space. Steps in the analysis illustrated are:

* Initial broad-brush selection from gaia_source from 1.7 billion rows to around 20 million;
* further filtering of this selection on velocity with respect to the Local Standard of Rest via kinematic transformations expressed in user-defined functions;
* transformation from Spark to Pandas data frame for input into a third-party implementation of the unsupervised ML clustering algorithm (HDBSCAN = "hierarchical density-based clustering and noise").

## To Do:
* Add LSR cut to the good sources (FIX the LSR cut causing issues?)
* Create a series of plots to show the clustering
* Select known and "predicted" white dwarfs and isolate the clusters containing these examples.

%spark.pyspark

def vector_to_array(col):
    def to_array_(v):
        return v.toArray().tolist()
    # Important: asNondeterministic requires Spark 2.3 or later
    # It can be safely removed i.e.
    # return udf(to_array_, ArrayType(DoubleType()))(col)
    # but at the cost of decreased performance
    return udf(to_array_, ArrayType(DoubleType())).asNondeterministic()(col)
    
    
def queryableSpuriousSources(filename):
    '''opens result from ML_cuts and makes queryable '''

    QC_cuts = spark.read.parquet('file:///user/dcr//ML_cuts/results/allDataMatchPS1.parquet')
    QC_cuts = QC_cuts.withColumn("probability", vector_to_array(col("probability")))\
                       .select(['source_id', 'prediction'] + [col("probability")[i] for i in range(2)])\
                        .withColumn('confidence', greatest(col('probability[0]'), col('probability[1]')))\
                        .select(['source_id', 'prediction', 'confidence'])\
                        .withColumnRenamed('prediction', 'is_good')
     
    QC_cuts.createOrReplaceTempView('dcr_spurious_sources')

queryableSpuriousSources(filename = 'file:///user/dcr//ML_cuts/results/allDataMatchPS1.parquet', )
# source_id == gaia edr3 source id
#   is_good == flag for good astrometric sources (0.0 = bad, 1.0 = good)
# confidence == confidence in prediction.

spark.catalog.listTables()

paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
def selectPlotType(x, y, plotType = 'scatter', ax = False, cmap = None, color = None,
                  label = None, s = 1, white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True,
                  alpha = 1.0):
    if plotType == 'scatter':
        scatter(x, y, ax = ax,
                color = color, label = label, s = s, alpha = alpha)
    elif plotType == 'kdeHeatmap':
         kdeHeatmap(x, y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
           white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar)
    elif plotType == '2Dhist':
         hist2d(x,y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
           white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar)
    elif plotType == '2DhistSub':
         hist2dSubplots(x,y, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, 
           white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = cbar)
    else: raise nameError('plotType must be one of ["scatter", "kdeHeatmap", "2Dhist", 2DhistSub]')
        
def kdeHeatmap(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True):
    '''creates a kdeHeatmap'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)

    # Evaluate a gaussian kde on a regular grid of nbins x nbins over data extents
    nbins=bins
    k = kde.gaussian_kde([x,y])
    xi, yi = np.mgrid[x.min():x.max():nbins*1j, y.min():y.max():nbins*1j]
    zi = k(np.vstack([xi.flatten(), yi.flatten()]))

    # Make the plot
    im = ax.pcolormesh(xi, yi, zi.reshape(xi.shape), shading='auto', cmap = cmap)
    
#     if cbar:
#         add_colorbar(cmap = cmap, im = im)
    
def scatter(x,y, ax = False, color = None, label = None, s = 1, alpha = 1.0):
    '''creates a scatter plot'''
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    ax.scatter(x, y, marker = '.', s = s, c = color, label = label, alpha = alpha)
    

def add_colorbar(cmap, im):
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    h = im[0]
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=np.min(h), vmax=np.max(h)))
    plt.colorbar(sm)
    
def hist2dSubplots(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True):
    '''creates a 2dhist plot'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)
    im = ax.hist2d(x, y, bins=bins, cmap=cmap)
    if cbar:
        addColorbarSubplots(cmap = cmap, im = im, ax = ax)

def addColorbarSubplots(cmap, im, ax):
    from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable
    h = im[0]
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes('right', size='5%', pad=0.05)
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=plt.Normalize(vmin=np.min(h), vmax=np.max(h)))
    plt.colorbar(sm, cax = cax)
    
    
def hist2d(x,y, ax = False, cmap = 'cividis', white_nan = False, bins = 100, cbar = True):
    '''creates a 2dhist plot'''
    
    if not ax:
        ax = plt.figure(111)
    if white_nan:
        cmap = whiteNan(cmap)
    im = ax.hist2d(x, y, bins=bins, cmap=cmap)
    if cbar:
        add_colorbar(cmap = cmap, im = im)
    
def whiteNan(cmap):
    '''adds white base for colormaps'''
    
    from matplotlib import cm
    from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
    
    cmap = cm.get_cmap(cmap, 256)
    newcolors = cmap(np.linspace(0, 1, 256))
    white = np.array([1, 1, 1, 0])
    newcolors[:2, :] = white
    cmap = ListedColormap(newcolors)
    return cmap

paragraphs.title: def CAMD
paragraphs.text:
%spark.pyspark
def CAMD(passbands, catalogues, colors = ['k', 'darkred', 'darkblue'], ms = 1, save = False, colorbar = False,
         labels = None, plotType = 'scatter', cmap = 'cividis', bins = 100, limit = 25000, title = None):
    '''plot an observational Hertzsprung-Russell diagram (aka colour / absolute magnitude diagram)
    for the unclassified sample to show the problem,
    include the photometric consistency filter to show the problem is astrometric in addition to photometric '''
    
    import matplotlib.pylab as plt
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (9.0, 9.0))
    c = -1
    quick_plot_filter = f' WHERE MOD(source_id, {limit}) = 0'
    for i in catalogues:
        c+=1
        if type(ms) == list:
            s = ms[c]
        else: s = ms
        if type(labels) == type(None):
            label = i
        else: label = labels[c]
            
        if plotType == 'scatter':
            color = colors[c]
        else: color = None
        
        tmp_df = spark.sql(f"SELECT phot_{passbands[0]}_mean_mag + 5.0*LOG10(parallax/100.0) AS m_{passbands[0]}, \
                            {passbands[1]} FROM {i} {quick_plot_filter}")

        tmp_df = tmp_df.toPandas().dropna()
        selectPlotType(x = tmp_df[f'{passbands[1]}'], y = tmp_df[f'm_{passbands[0]}'], 
                      plotType = plotType, ax = ax, cmap = cmap, color = color,
                      label = label, s = s, white_nan = True, bins = bins, cbar = colorbar)
        
    plt.ylim(18.0, -10.0)
    plt.xlim(-0.5, 3)
    plt.ylabel('Stellar brightness (absolute G magnitude) -->', fontsize = 16)
    plt.xlabel('<-- Stellar temperature (G - RP magnitude)', fontsize = 16)
    if plotType == 'scatter':
        lgnd = plt.legend(fontsize = 12, markerscale = 1)
        for i in range(len(catalogues)):
            lgnd.legendHandles[i]._sizes = [25]
    else:
        plt.title(title)
        
    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            savefigs(save)

paragraphs.title: Spark df manipulations
LSR Function definitions
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# Generic functions used later

def convDegRad(args, units="degrees"):
    '''args in km/sTransforms degrees to radians or returns radians if in radians
        units - ['degrees', 'radians'] Units of args'''

    if units == 'degrees':
        args = [i*pi/180 for i in args]
    return args

def convMasKm(args, parallax, units= 'mas/yr'):
    '''Converts data from mas/yr to km/s
        units - ['mas/yr', 'km/s'] Units of args'''
    
    if units == 'mas/yr':
        k = 4.74057
        args = [i/parallax * 4.74057 for i in args]
    elif units != 'km/s':
        raise ValueError("Input proper motion values in either mas/yr or km/s")
    return args

def matrix_multiplication_arrays(A,B):
    '''Matrix multiplication of Matrix A and B if both are either lists or numpy.arrays'''
    
    if np.shape(A)[1] != np.shape(B)[0]:
        return 'Invalid matrix shape'
    else:
        n,m = np.shape(A)[0], np.shape(B)[1]
        M = np.zeros((n,m))
        
        for i in range(n):
            for j in range(len(B[0])):
                E=0
                for k in range(len(B)):
#                     print('A{}{}*B{}{}'.format(i,k,k,j))
                    E += A[i][k]*B[k][j]
                M[i,j] = E
#                 print('\n')
        return M
        
# Functions to perform the LSR cut

def create_Matrix_A(ra, dec, coord_units = 'degrees'):
    '''creates Matrix A, where A = [[cos(ra)*cos(dec), -sin(ra), -cos(ra)*sin(dec)],
                                     [sin(ra)*cos(dec),  cos(ra), -sin(ra)*sin(dec)],
                                     [sin(dec),             0,     cos(dec)]])'''
    
#     if all(v is None for v in {data, ra, dec}):
#         raise ValueError("Expected input either as array or 'ra' and 'dec' values")
#     if data is None:
#         if any(v is None for v in {ra,dec}):
#             raise ValueError("Expected input either as array or 'ra' and 'dec' values")

    ra,dec = convDegRad([ra,dec], units = coord_units)  # Ensures radians
        
    A = np.array([[cos(ra)*cos(dec), -sin(ra), -cos(ra)*sin(dec)],
              [sin(ra)*cos(dec), cos(ra), -sin(ra)*sin(dec)],
              [sin(dec), 0, cos(dec)]])
    return A

def create_matrix_C(pmra, pmdec, parallax = None, radial_velocity = 0.0, units = 'mas/yr'):
    '''creates Matrix C, where C = [radial_velocity, pmra, pmdec]'''
    
    if parallax == None and units == 'mas/yr':
        raise ValueError("Parallax value must be supplied if proper motion units are 'mas/yr'")

    pmra,pmdec = convMasKm([pmra, pmdec], parallax = parallax, units = units)  # Ensures proper motions in km/s
    C = np.array([[radial_velocity, pmra, pmdec]]).T
    
    
    return C
    
def conv_Galactic_LSR(G, magnitude = True):
    '''Calculates magnitude of LSR velocity give U,V,W velocity.
    
    SEE ALSO
        v_sun values from Schonrich, R., Binney, J., & Dehnen, W. 2010 | 
        DOI: 10.1111/j.1365-2966.2010.16253.x'''
        
    v_sun = [11.1, 12.24, 7.25]
    lsr = np.asarray(G).T + v_sun
    
    if magnitude == True:
        v_lsr = np.sqrt(np.sum([i**2 for i in lsr]))
        return v_lsr
    return lsr
    
def LSR_conv(ra, dec, parallax, pmra, pmdec, coord_units = 'degrees', pm_units='mas/yr', radial_velocity = 0.0, magnitude = True):
    '''Converts proper motions from ra, dec to LSR velocity
    SEE ALSO
         Method from: Johnson, Dean R. H., Soderblom, David R. DOI: 10.1086/114370
    '''
    
    T = [[-0.05646624, -0.87325802, -0.48397519],
         [ 0.49253617, -0.44602111,  0.74731071],
         [-0.86845823, -0.19617746,  0.4552963 ]]

    A = create_Matrix_A(ra,dec, coord_units=coord_units)   # forms Marix A
    B = matrix_multiplication_arrays(T, A)  # forms Matrix B
    
    C = create_matrix_C(pmra,pmdec,parallax, units = pm_units, radial_velocity = radial_velocity)    # forms Matrix C
    G = matrix_multiplication_arrays(B,C) # Calculates U, W, V

    v_lsr = conv_Galactic_LSR(G, magnitude = magnitude) # Calculates velocity magnitude in LSR coords
    
    return v_lsr

# This function needs to be called by the UDF, all optional parameters are set as required - e.g. show_velocity = False.

def LSR_cut(ra,dec,parallax,pmra,pmdec, 
            cut = 60, coord_units = 'degrees', 
            pm_units='mas/yr', show_velocity = False):
    '''Calculates LSR velocity through LSR_conv and returns boolean if satisfies cut condition'''
    
    v = LSR_conv(ra,dec,parallax,pmra,pmdec, coord_units=coord_units, pm_units=pm_units)
    if show_velocity == True:
        print(v)
    if v < cut:
        return 1
    if v > cut:
        return 0
        

from pyspark.sql.types import IntegerType

# finally, register the top-level user-defined function for inclusion in queries
spark.udf.register("udf_lsr_cut", LSR_cut, IntegerType())

paragraphs.title: def equatorial to Cartesian
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def deg_conv_factor(unit = 'degrees'):
    '''return conversion factor to radians'''
    
    if unit == 'degrees': return pi/180
    elif unit == 'radians': return 1
    else: raise ValueError('Please enter a valid unit for angle ["degrees", "radians"]')
        
def plx_conv_factor(unit = 'mas'):
    '''return conversion factor to arcsec'''
    
    if unit == 'mas': return 10**-3
    elif unit == 'arcsec': return 1
    else: raise ValueError('Please enter a valid unit for parallax ["mas", "arcsec"]')
        
def equatorial_to_cartesian(df, drop_df = True, coord_units = 'degrees'):
    '''Converts equatorial coordinates to cartesian from a spark dataframe
    
    RETURNS
        sql.DataFrame with cartesian coordinates in parsec'''
    
    trig_funcs = [[1, cos, cos], [1, cos, sin], [1, sin]]
    trig_funcs = reshape_input(trig_funcs, desired_length = 3)

    cols = [['parallax','dec', 'ra'], ['parallax','dec','ra'], ['parallax','dec']]
    cols = reshape_input(cols, desired_length = 3)
    signs = [1, 1, 1]

    matrix_cols=[]
    plx_conv = plx_conv_factor('mas')
    
    for i in range(len(signs)):
        a = 1/(col(cols[i][0])*plx_conv) * \
            element_transform(trig_funcs[i][1], cols[i][1], col_units = 'degrees') * \
            element_transform(trig_funcs[i][2], cols[i][2], col_units = 'degrees')

        matrix_cols.append(a)

    names = ['X_pc', 'Y_pc', 'Z_pc']
    df = drop_DataFrame(df = df, matrix_cols = matrix_cols, signs = signs,
                        names = names, drop_df = drop_df)

    return df

paragraphs.title: HDBSCAN clusterer info
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def insert_to_df(df, name, insert_data, index=-1):
    '''Creates column in DataFrame if does not exist, or replaces values if already present.'''
    if name in df.columns:
        df[name] = insert_data
    else:
        if index==-1:               # Adds the data to end of the DataFrame
            index=len(df.columns)
        df.insert(index, name, insert_data)
    return df

def clustering_info(clusterer, add_to_data=False, df=[], index=-1):
    '''
    REQUIRED
        clusterer = output clusterer from HDBSCAN.
        
    OPTIONAL
        add_to_data = [boolean] Add results to df or return as arrays.
        df = [Required if add_to_data = True] DataFrame to add results.
        index = [Default = -1] Column location to add results.
        
    RETURNS
        *groups = Cluster labels for each point in the dataset given to fit(). 
                   Noisy samples are given the label -1.
        *prob = The strength with which each sample is a member of its assigned cluster.
        *persistence = A score of how persistent each cluster is. 
                       A score of 1.0 represents a perfectly stable cluster. 
    
        if add_to_data = False, returns [groups, prob, persistence] as seperate arrays.
        if add_to_data = True - returns df(DataFrame), persistence (array) - Must provide df to add.
        
        (*From HDBSCAN - in SEE ALSO)
        
    SEE ALSO
        https://hdbscan.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
    '''
    # probabilities and group for each object
    prob=clusterer.probabilities_
    groups=clusterer.labels_

    # Info on persistence of groups
    persistence=clusterer.cluster_persistence_
    
    print('Number of Groups = ', max(groups)+1) 
    if add_to_data == False:
        return groups, prob, persistence
    
    if add_to_data == True:
        df=insert_to_df(df, 'group', groups, index=index)
        df=insert_to_df(df,'probability', prob, index=index)
        return df, persistence
    
def clustering_prediction(clusterer, points_to_predict, cols, add_to_data=False, index=-1):
    '''
    REQUIRED
        clusterer = output clusterer from HDBSCAN.
        points_to_predict = DataFrame of objects to predict relationships to clustered data.
        cols = list of columns used for clustering.
    
    OPTIONAL
        add_to_data = [boolean] Add results to points_to_predict or return as arrays.
        index = [Default = -1] Column location to add results.
        
    RETURNS
        *group = The predicted labels of the points_to_predict
        *prob = The soft cluster scores for each of the points_to_predict
        
        if add_to_data=False, returns [group, prob] as seperate arrays.
        if add_to_data=True - returns df(DataFrame) with group and prob added.
        
        (*From HDBSCAN - in SEE ALSO)
        
    SEE ALSO
        https://hdbscan.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
    '''
    
    groups, prob = hdbscan.approximate_predict(clusterer, points_to_predict[cols])
    if add_to_data == False:
        return groups, prob
    
    if add_to_data == True:
        points_to_predict=insert_to_df(points_to_predict, 'group', groups, index=index)
        points_to_predict=insert_to_df(points_to_predict,'probability', prob, index=index)
        return points_to_predict

%pyspark
def randomise_color(group):
    np.random.seed(group)
    return np.random.randint(0,255)
    
def cluster_projections(df, save = False, cmap = 'plasma', fontsize = 14):
    
    from matplotlib import cm
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = fontsize
    plt.figure(3, figsize = (16.18, 10.0))
    plt.subplot(111, projection="mollweide")
    plt.grid(True)

    cmap = cm.get_cmap(cmap, 255)
    
    randomise_color(group = 1)
    color = [randomise_color(i) for i in df.group]

    x = (df['l'] - 180.0) * np.pi / 180.0
    y = (df['b'] * np.pi / 180.0)
    plt.title('eDR3 CLusters', fontsize = 12)
    plt.scatter(x,y, marker = '.', s = 10, cmap = cmap, c = color)
    plt.xlabel('Galactic Longnitude (l)')
    plt.ylabel('Galactic Latitude (b)')
    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            savefigs(save)
    plt.show()
    
cluster_projections(df = df[df['group'] != -1], save = False, cmap = 'plasma', fontsize = 14)

%pyspark

def clusterSubProjections(df, save = False, cmap = 'plasma', fontsize = 14):
    
    from matplotlib import cm
    
    fig = plt.figure(3, figsize = (16.18, 10.0))
    plt.rcParams['font.size'] = fontsize
    
    l = (df['l'] - 180.0) * np.pi / 180.0
    cmap = cm.get_cmap(cmap, 255)
    randomise_color(group = 1)
    color = [randomise_color(i) for i in df.group]

    ax1 = plt.subplot(121, projection='polar')
    ax1.set_theta_zero_location('W', offset=90)
    ax1.scatter(l, df['parallax'], c = color, cmap = cmap, s = 3)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Galactic Longnitude (l)')
    ax1.set_xlim(-np.pi, np.pi)
    ax1.set_ylim(0)
    ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(-np.pi, np.pi, np.pi/6))
    
    ax2 = plt.subplot(122, projection="mollweide")
    ax2.grid(True)
    y = (df['b'] * np.pi / 180.0)
    ax2.set_title('eDR3 CLusters', fontsize = 12)
    ax2.scatter(l, y, marker = '.', s = 3, cmap = cmap, c = color)
    ax2.set_xlabel('Galactic Longnitude (l)')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Galactic Latitude (b)')
    if save:
        if not dev_run:
            savefigs(save)
    plt.show()
    
clusterSubProjections(df = df[df['group'] != -1], save = False, cmap = 'plasma', fontsize = 14)
